    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-14T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-14T18:00:00-05:00" n="40"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d40">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/521</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-14T23:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 14, 1918, 11 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.51 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8670. The Foreign Office has approached me informally on the desirability of
                    setting up some kind of a blockade council. They hope that the project will
                    materialize in the near future, but meanwhile suggest that the establishment
                    here of an international subcommittee <pb facs="0124" n="958" xml:id="pg_958"/>
                    on rationing and statistics would make the practical working of blockade
                    operations smoother and easier.</p>
                <p>Therefore it is evident that questions on these subjects must arise in the course
                    of our negotiations with neutrals, and that it would be convenient to have some
                    international body that could give us authoritatively the statistical facts
                    involved. The Foreign Office proposes, therefore, to ask Mr. <persName>R. E.
                        Harwood</persName> to serve on such a committee and to ask the Italian and
                    French Governments each to nominate a member. In view of this action they
                    inquire whether the Government of the United States would be disposed to do
                    likewise. Should you consent to this, I would suggest that I be authorized to
                    designate <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> of my
                    staff.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
